            . On the 19th of April, as I was going down <placeName id="t18290611-341-crimeloc1788">Holborn</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290611-341-crimeloc1788" type="placeName" value="Holborn"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290611-341-crimeloc1788" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290611-341-off1786 t18290611-341-crimeloc1788"></join>, I wanted my handkerchief and missed it; I had not felt any thing done to me - I had it but a few minutes before; I saw the prisoner close behind me, and the watchman had the handkerchief.</p>
               <p>GEORGE FORDYCE. I am a watchman. At ten minutes past eleven o'clock the prosecutor walked by me with a lady, the prisoner was close behind him - I followed, and saw him draw this handkerchief out of his pocket - the prosecutor seemed to feel some one pulling at his pocket; the prisoner threw it behind him, and it fell on my foot; the prosecutor turned, and said,</p>
               <p>"He has got my handkerchief;" I said, "No; I have it."</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I had been drinking, and was going home - I passed this watchman, and saw him pick up the handkerchief; he laid hold of me, and said he saw me take it; I am a stranger in London, and am a native of Liverpool. <rs id="t18290611-341-verdict1789" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290611-341-verdict1789" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 27.</p>

               <p>
                  <rs id="t18290611-341-punish1790" type="punishmentDescription">
